    summary: "On April 21, 2026, IRCC published a citizenship update. Permanent residents nearing eligibility should review their physical presence records and language evidence.",
    body: "On April 21, 2026, IRCC published a citizenship update. Permanent residents nearing eligibility should review their physical presence records and language evidence.\n\nTo qualify for Canadian citizenship under the Citizenship Act, a permanent resident must have been physically present in Canada for at least 1,095 days during the five-year period immediately before the application date. Days spent in Canada as a temporary resident count for half a day, up to a maximum of 365 days. Applicants between 18 and 54 must also demonstrate language proficiency at CLB 4 or higher in English or French and pass the citizenship knowledge test.\n\nCitizenship applications are among the most evidence-sensitive files at IRCC. Practitioners advise applicants to build their physical presence calculation with documentary backup — passport stamps, CBSA travel history, employment records, school enrolment records, lease agreements, and tax filings. Discrepancies between declared days and travel-history records are the most common trigger for a request for additional information.\n\nFor applicants whose physical presence is borderline, IRCC may refer the file to a citizenship judge for a hearing, particularly where there are gaps in evidence or where the applicant has spent extended periods abroad. Recent Federal Court decisions have emphasised the duty of officers to grapple with the evidence on the record before refusing on residency grounds.\n\nSettlement-sector analyst Nadia Petrov said the change \"shifts pressure onto provinces to expand their PNP capacity, particularly in healthcare-heavy regions.\"\n\nChrome Visa Solutions reviews citizenship eligibility on a free 15-minute call. We can help applicants determine their exact qualifying day, identify gaps that warrant supporting affidavits, and prepare a clean physical-presence calculation that withstands officer review.",
