    id: "n0326",
    slug: "alberta-aaip-invites-330-candidates-in-alberta-opportunity-stream-draw",
    title: "Alberta AAIP invites 330 candidates in Alberta Opportunity Stream draw",
    summary: "The Alberta Provincial Nominee Program (AAIP) held a Alberta Opportunity Stream draw on April 12, 2026, inviting 330 candidates with a minimum ranking score of 90.",
    body: "The Alberta Provincial Nominee Program (AAIP) held a Alberta Opportunity Stream draw on April 12, 2026, inviting 330 candidates with a minimum ranking score of 90.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the AAIP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Alberta, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Alberta Opportunity Stream, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The AAIP reviews provincial applications within 69 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Alberta adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Alberta prioritising occupations in construction, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, AAIP has issued approximately 5,345 invitations across all streams.\n\nSenior policy analyst Aiden Park said the move \"reflects a labour-market-led shift that began with the 2023 category-based draws.\"\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within three weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
