    body: "The Yukon Provincial Nominee Program (YNP) held a Skilled Worker draw on April 07, 2026, inviting 188 candidates with a minimum ranking score of 89.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the YNP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Yukon, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Skilled Worker, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The YNP reviews provincial applications within 96 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Yukon adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Yukon prioritising occupations in manufacturing, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, YNP has issued approximately 5,171 invitations across all streams.\n\n\"The Federal Court has been increasingly receptive to procedural fairness arguments — this is consistent with that trend,\" noted IRPP fellow Élise Bouchard.\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within four weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
