    body: "On February 12, 2026, an update affected the Start-up Visa Program. Entrepreneurs and incubators should review the change.\n\nThe Start-up Visa is a pathway to permanent residence for entrepreneurs whose innovative business idea has been backed by a designated business support organization — a venture capital fund, angel investor group, or business incubator approved by IRCC. The program admits up to five co-founders per venture, each of whom applies independently for permanent residence.\n\nRecent reforms aim to address two concerns: program backlog, which has stretched processing times beyond the original two-year target, and essentiality, which IRCC officers assess to ensure that each co-founder named in the commitment letter is actually material to the business. Co-founders judged non-essential have seen refusals upheld at the Federal Court level in recent years.\n\nFor entrepreneurs considering the Start-up Visa, the practical steps are: identify a venture concept that meaningfully addresses a Canadian or global market gap, secure a designated organization willing to issue a commitment letter (the bar for which has risen), prepare a business plan that withstands IRCC officer scrutiny, and build the documentary record demonstrating each co-founder's essentiality before filing.\n\nImmigration lawyer Catherine Sauvé warned that \"candidates outside the favoured category should reconsider their timing — and their backup plan.\"\n\nChrome Visa Solutions provides Start-up Visa consultation in partnership with designated venture capital and incubator partners. We assess concept-fit, prepare commitment-letter applications, and build the essentiality file. Initial consultations are 60 minutes and free for venture teams of three or more.",
