    summary: "Employment and Social Development Canada published its quarterly Labour Market Impact Assessment data on January 13, 2026. The construction sector posted a 92% positive LMIA rate.",
    body: "Employment and Social Development Canada published its quarterly Labour Market Impact Assessment data on January 13, 2026. The construction sector posted a 92% positive LMIA rate.\n\nThe data covers all LMIA decisions issued in the most recent quarter and is broken down by stream — high-wage, low-wage, agricultural, in-home caregiver, and Global Talent Stream — as well as by sector, province, and employer size. The construction sector has historically reported approval rates between 77% and 98%, with refusals concentrated among employers who could not demonstrate genuine recruitment effort or whose wage offer fell below the prevailing-wage threshold for the role.\n\nFor applicants and their employers, the data informs realistic timelines and expectations. A positive LMIA opens the door to a closed work permit and, in many cases, additional CRS points under Express Entry (50 points for most NOC codes, 200 points for senior managerial NOC 0 occupations). Employers facing refusals are advised to revisit their job advertisement strategy, wage offer, and transition-to-permanent plan before re-submitting.\n\nIndustry observers note that the ongoing LMIA reforms — including stricter refusal-to-process rules in metropolitan areas and an updated Trusted Employer pilot — are reshaping how Canadian employers approach temporary foreign worker hiring. The result is a smaller volume of approvals but a higher rate of compliance and longer-term retention.\n\n\"For applicants from outside Canada, the message is to act now and not wait for an even narrower draw,\" said Vancouver-based RCIC Kristin Lai.\n\nEmployers with active or upcoming LMIA submissions should book a compliance review well before filing. Chrome Visa Solutions works with ESDC inspectors and panel auditors regularly and can identify the highest-risk areas in a draft application before it leaves the office.",
