    body: "The Newfoundland and Labrador Provincial Nominee Program (NLPNP) held a Skilled Worker draw on December 21, 2025, inviting 980 candidates with a minimum CRS score of 704.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the NLPNP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Newfoundland and Labrador, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Skilled Worker, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The NLPNP reviews provincial applications within 114 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Newfoundland and Labrador adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Newfoundland and Labrador prioritising occupations in tech, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, NLPNP has issued approximately 917 invitations across all streams.\n\nSettlement-sector analyst Nadia Petrov said the change \"shifts pressure onto provinces to expand their PNP capacity, particularly in healthcare-heavy regions.\"\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within four weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
