    body: "IRCC's monthly processing-time update for October 2025 shows study permit (SDS) applications now sit at 7 months end-to-end.\n\nThe published figures are based on 80th-percentile completion rates and exclude time required for biometrics, medicals, and security checks. They reflect the average time from receipt of a complete application to final decision under standard processing. Files with complex inadmissibility findings, security flags, or sponsorship interview requirements can take materially longer.\n\nFor applicants currently in queue, this benchmark is best used as a planning tool rather than a guarantee. IRCC's online status tools provide individual file updates, but real-time movement is uneven: some files receive medicals, biometrics, and approval within weeks of submission, while others sit in queue for months before assignment to an officer. The best predictor of file movement remains the completeness and clarity of the original submission.\n\nFor applicants planning to submit, the published time also informs strategy decisions: whether to apply outland or in-Canada, whether to pursue a parallel temporary residence option to bridge the wait, and whether to request priority processing for humanitarian or compassionate reasons where applicable.\n\n\"Anyone with a profile in the pool should refresh their language scores and re-confirm their NOC code immediately,\" said Halifax-based RCIC Pierre Allard.\n\nChrome Visa Solutions tracks IRCC processing times monthly and publishes alerts when material movements occur. Clients can request a free file-readiness check to identify documents most likely to trigger a request for further information once the file is opened.",
