    body: "On August 29, 2025, an update was issued regarding private refugee sponsorship cap raised. Refugee claimants, sponsors, and counsel should note the following operational changes.\n\nEligibility, processing, and appeal rights are the core areas affected by this update. Counsel should confirm the impact on in-progress files within 30 days of the announcement. Both inland claimants and resettled refugees fall within scope, although the specific operational changes may affect the two streams differently.\n\nThe Refugee Protection Division (RPD) of the Immigration and Refugee Board hears in-Canada claims, while the Refugee Appeal Division (RAD) reviews most negative RPD decisions on legal and factual grounds. Pre-Removal Risk Assessments fall under IRCC jurisdiction and apply to claimants whose RPD claims were rejected and who are subject to removal. The interaction between these streams is highly procedural and often misunderstood.\n\nPrivate sponsorship — through Sponsorship Agreement Holders or Groups of Five — remains a critical resettlement pathway, particularly for refugees whose UNHCR resettlement priority does not match the timing of their need. The Resettlement Assistance Program funds initial settlement supports for government-assisted refugees, while private sponsors take on the financial commitment for sponsored refugees during the first year in Canada.\n\nImmigration lawyer Catherine Sauvé warned that \"candidates outside the favoured category should reconsider their timing — and their backup plan.\"\n\nRefugee claimants and sponsors should consult with experienced counsel before submitting. The evidentiary and credibility thresholds at the RPD are demanding and inconsistent country-by-country. Chrome Visa Solutions partners with senior immigration counsel for refugee files and offers initial consultations in both English and French.",
