    body: "The Saskatchewan Provincial Nominee Program (SINP) held a Health Professionals draw on August 18, 2025, inviting 712 candidates with a minimum CRS score of 532.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the SINP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Saskatchewan, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Health Professionals, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The SINP reviews provincial applications within 86 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Saskatchewan adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Saskatchewan prioritising occupations in construction, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, SINP has issued approximately 848 invitations across all streams.\n\nImmigration lawyer Catherine Sauvé warned that \"candidates outside the favoured category should reconsider their timing — and their backup plan.\"\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within two weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
