    id: "n0273",
    slug: "manitoba-mpnp-invites-145-candidates-in-business-investor-stream-draw",
    title: "Manitoba MPNP invites 145 candidates in Business Investor Stream draw",
    summary: "The Manitoba Provincial Nominee Program (MPNP) held a Business Investor Stream draw on July 24, 2025, inviting 145 candidates with a minimum ranking score of 88.",
    body: "The Manitoba Provincial Nominee Program (MPNP) held a Business Investor Stream draw on July 24, 2025, inviting 145 candidates with a minimum ranking score of 88.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the MPNP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Manitoba, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Business Investor Stream, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The MPNP reviews provincial applications within 75 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Manitoba adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Manitoba prioritising occupations in tech, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, MPNP has issued approximately 5,979 invitations across all streams.\n\nSenior policy analyst Aiden Park said the move \"reflects a labour-market-led shift that began with the 2023 category-based draws.\"\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within four weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
