    body: "The Ontario Provincial Nominee Program (OINP) held a French-Speaking Skilled Worker draw on July 11, 2025, inviting 110 candidates with a minimum ranking score of 90.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the OINP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Ontario, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the French-Speaking Skilled Worker, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The OINP reviews provincial applications within 112 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Ontario adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Ontario prioritising occupations in construction, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, OINP has issued approximately 4,259 invitations across all streams.\n\nCILA spokesperson Daniel Park noted that \"the change does not alter eligibility, but it materially changes the strategy for profile creation.\"\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within two weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
