    summary: "On June 09, 2025, IRCC issued an update affecting family class sponsorship. The change has immediate implications for in-progress and prospective applicants.",
    body: "On June 09, 2025, IRCC issued an update affecting family class sponsorship. The change has immediate implications for in-progress and prospective applicants.\n\nFamily class sponsorship is the second-largest pathway to permanent residence in Canada after the economic class. Eligible sponsors include Canadian citizens and permanent residents over 18 who undertake a binding 3- to 20-year financial commitment to support the sponsored relative, depending on the relationship class. The sponsored relative must pass admissibility on medical, security, and criminality grounds.\n\nSponsors should review their evidence portfolio in light of the update. The bar for proving a genuine and continuing relationship in spousal applications has risen materially in recent years, with officers now expecting joint financial accounts, shared utility bills, joint travel records, photographic evidence with timestamps, and corroborating affidavits from third parties. Lower-evidence files are increasingly referred to interview or refused outright.\n\nApplications under the parents-and-grandparents stream remain capacity-constrained: IRCC accepts a fixed number of complete applications each year, drawn from a pool of sponsors who submitted an interest-to-sponsor form during the open window. The 2026 intake is expected to follow the lottery model with a published acceptance ceiling. The Super Visa remains an alternative for sponsors who cannot secure a PGP intake spot.\n\n\"The Federal Court has been increasingly receptive to procedural fairness arguments — this is consistent with that trend,\" noted IRPP fellow Élise Bouchard.\n\nChrome Visa Solutions offers a free 20-minute review for affected sponsorship files, including a checklist of the evidence that most often makes or breaks an application at first review. We will publish a follow-up brief with category-specific guidance within the next two weeks.",
