    summary: "The British Columbia Provincial Nominee Program (BC PNP) held a International Graduate draw on March 25, 2025, inviting 712 candidates with a minimum CRS score of 529.",
    body: "The British Columbia Provincial Nominee Program (BC PNP) held a International Graduate draw on March 25, 2025, inviting 712 candidates with a minimum CRS score of 529.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the BC PNP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in British Columbia, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the International Graduate, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The BC PNP reviews provincial applications within 84 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from British Columbia adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of British Columbia prioritising occupations in agriculture, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, BC PNP has issued approximately 2,300 invitations across all streams.\n\n\"Anyone with a profile in the pool should refresh their language scores and re-confirm their NOC code immediately,\" said Halifax-based RCIC Pierre Allard.\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within two weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
