    body: "On March 15, 2025, Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship Canada issued a public update affecting the Atlantic Immigration Program. The change takes effect in the coming weeks and is expected to affect both pending and future applicants.\n\nThe update was published as an operational bulletin to IRCC officers and is consistent with commitments tabled in the 2024–2026 Immigration Levels Plan. Stakeholders including registered consultants, immigration lawyers, settlement agencies, and provincial counterparts have been notified through the Department's regular consultation channels.\n\nPractitioners are reviewing the bulletin in detail to assess how it will be applied to in-progress files. Early indications suggest that applications submitted before the effective date will be processed under the rules in force at the time of receipt, with new submissions following the updated framework. IRCC has confirmed that no fee changes accompany this update, but procedural changes may affect both the documentation required and the time-to-decision.\n\nThe change reflects a broader pattern of IRCC modernisation under the Department's renewed mandate. Other recent updates have included shorter spousal open work permit processing windows, expanded category-based Express Entry selection, and the rollout of the Authorized Paid Representative reporting framework.\n\nSettlement-sector analyst Nadia Petrov said the change \"shifts pressure onto provinces to expand their PNP capacity, particularly in healthcare-heavy regions.\"\n\nAffected applicants should review their file with a CICC-licensed RCIC or Canadian-trained immigration lawyer before the effective date. Chrome Visa Solutions will publish a follow-up brief outlining the specific scenarios most likely to be impacted, including in-progress applications, refusal-recovery cases, and clients still in the profile-creation stage.",
