    body: "The Manitoba Provincial Nominee Program (MPNP) held a Skilled Worker Overseas draw on February 24, 2025, inviting 78 candidates with a minimum ranking score of 64.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the MPNP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Manitoba, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Skilled Worker Overseas, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The MPNP reviews provincial applications within 60 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Manitoba adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Manitoba prioritising occupations in agriculture, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, MPNP has issued approximately 5,139 invitations across all streams.\n\n\"For applicants from outside Canada, the message is to act now and not wait for an even narrower draw,\" said Vancouver-based RCIC Kristin Lai.\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within three weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
