    body: "On February 14, 2025, IRCC published an update to the International Student Program: canada caps international student study permits at 437,000 for the upcoming intake year.\n\nThe change is part of a broader package of reforms to the International Student Program announced over the past 18 months. That package includes a national cap on study permit approvals, mandatory provincial attestation letters in most jurisdictions, tightened Designated Learning Institution oversight, and a revised Post-Graduation Work Permit eligibility framework based on field of study and TEER alignment.\n\nDesignated learning institutions, provincial regulators, and prospective applicants should review the operational bulletin in full. The update applies to applications submitted on or after the effective date. Existing students with a valid study permit are not directly affected unless they are renewing or transferring institutions, in which case the new rules apply.\n\nFor applicants currently preparing a study permit submission, the practical implications include: securing the provincial attestation letter before lodging the federal application, mapping their intended program against the latest PGWP-eligible field-of-study list, and ensuring the receiving institution remains on the active DLI list at the time of decision. Refusals on these grounds are non-refundable and complicate future applications.\n\nCalgary RCIC Rachel Yim said the development is \"the clearest signal yet that IRCC is willing to use category-based selection as a sustained tool, not a one-off.\"\n\nChrome Visa Solutions advises prospective international students to book a 30-minute consult before submitting if they intend to use a study permit as a route to permanent residence. The PGWP-to-PR pipeline is increasingly tied to specific occupational categories, and program selection at the study-permit stage now has long-tail consequences.",
