    body: "The Alberta Provincial Nominee Program (AAIP) held a Alberta Express Entry draw on February 06, 2025, inviting 250 candidates with a minimum CRS score of 640.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the AAIP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Alberta, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Alberta Express Entry, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The AAIP reviews provincial applications within 119 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Alberta adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Alberta prioritising occupations in agriculture, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, AAIP has issued approximately 5,497 invitations across all streams.\n\nImmigration lawyer Catherine Sauvé warned that \"candidates outside the favoured category should reconsider their timing — and their backup plan.\"\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within two weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
