    body: "The Northwest Territories Provincial Nominee Program (NTNP) held a Skilled Worker draw on January 07, 2025, inviting 145 candidates with a minimum CRS score of 714.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the NTNP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in Northwest Territories, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Skilled Worker, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The NTNP reviews provincial applications within 78 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from Northwest Territories adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of Northwest Territories prioritising occupations in early childhood education, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, NTNP has issued approximately 3,481 invitations across all streams.\n\n\"Anyone with a profile in the pool should refresh their language scores and re-confirm their NOC code immediately,\" said Halifax-based RCIC Pierre Allard.\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within three weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
