    body: "On December 17, 2024, Employment and Social Development Canada confirmed: lmia processing fee rises to $1,000 per worker. Employers and applicants should plan for the change.\n\nThe update is the latest in a series of work-permit-stream recalibrations driven by labour market data and the federal Department's commitment to align temporary foreign worker policy with genuine labour shortages. The framework continues to distinguish between LMIA-based work permits — which require a positive Labour Market Impact Assessment from ESDC — and LMIA-exempt categories such as Intra-Company Transfers, post-graduation work permits, and spousal open work permits.\n\nExisting files in queue may continue to be processed under the previous rules, depending on the receipt date and the implementation plan published by IRCC. New submissions filed on or after the effective date will follow the updated framework. Compliance obligations for employers — including the requirement to maintain records for six years and to permit ESDC inspectors to enter the workplace — remain in force throughout the worker's permit period.\n\nFor affected workers, the most common questions concern bridging options: whether a current permit can be extended under the old rules, whether a new permit application can be lodged from inside Canada, and whether a permanent residence pathway remains accessible. The answer typically depends on the applicant's NOC code, the province in which they currently work, and the time remaining on their existing permit.\n\nSettlement-sector analyst Nadia Petrov said the change \"shifts pressure onto provinces to expand their PNP capacity, particularly in healthcare-heavy regions.\"\n\nEmployers should review their workforce planning and any pending LMIA submissions in light of the change. Chrome Visa Solutions offers a complimentary employer consultation to help businesses identify which positions remain viable, where switching to a PNP-based pathway makes more sense, and how to time their submissions to avoid quota exhaustion.",
