    body: "The British Columbia Provincial Nominee Program (BC PNP) held a Childcare draw on October 21, 2024, inviting 712 candidates with a minimum ranking score of 92.\n\nCandidates were drawn from the BC PNP Expression of Interest system, which ranks profiles using a points matrix that weighs work experience, education, language ability, employment in British Columbia, and family ties to the province. Streams aligned with Express Entry, like the Childcare, also require an active EE profile to be eligible for a provincial nomination.\n\nSuccessful applicants now have 45 days to submit a full provincial nomination application along with supporting evidence: language test results (IELTS, CELPIP, or TEF/TCF), educational credential assessments, employment records that map to a TEER 0–5 occupation, and proof of settlement funds. The BC PNP reviews provincial applications within 104 days under current service standards. Receiving a provincial nomination from British Columbia adds 600 CRS points to a candidate's federal Express Entry profile, effectively guaranteeing an Invitation to Apply at the next federal draw.\n\nThis draw fits a wider pattern of British Columbia prioritising occupations in early childhood education, in line with the province's labour market gap analysis published earlier this year. Year-to-date, BC PNP has issued approximately 3,372 invitations across all streams.\n\n\"The Federal Court has been increasingly receptive to procedural fairness arguments — this is consistent with that trend,\" noted IRPP fellow Élise Bouchard.\n\nCandidates not invited in this round but with active EOI profiles will remain in the pool for the next draw, typically held within three weeks. Chrome Visa Solutions recommends that candidates whose ranking score sits within 30 points of the cut-off review their language test schedule and verify whether a higher CLB band would lift them into invitation range.",
